# Project: hbot — Shared Runtime v2.4 Trading Desk

## What this is
Hummingbot-based market-making bot for BTC-USDT perpetual futures on Bitget.
Paper trading (Paper Engine v2 / PaperDesk v2) is the primary environment.
Live deployment requires passing all promotion gates and the go-live hardening checklist.

## Workspace layout
```
hbot/
  platform_lib/               # Shared infra library (market_data, execution, logging, contracts, core)
  simulation/                 # Paper simulation engine (desk, matching, portfolio, risk)
  simulation/bridge/          # HB connector bridge (hb_bridge, event fire, signal consumer)
  controllers/                # Trading logic
  controllers/runtime/kernel/ # Decomposed runtime kernel (controller, mixins, config)
  controllers/bots/           # Strategy lanes (bot1, bot5, bot6, bot7)
  controllers/paper_engine_v2/  # Re-export shim for simulation/ (backward compat)
  services/                   # Supporting microservices (kill_switch, reconciliation, signal, etc.)
  services/common/            # Re-export shims for platform_lib/ (backward compat)
  scripts/                    # Ops, analysis, and release scripts
  tests/                      # pytest test suite
  tests/architecture/         # Architectural contract tests (import boundaries, coverage minimums)
  tests/controllers/test_kernel/  # Kernel mixin unit tests
  tests/test_simulation/      # Simulation/bridge error path tests
  infra/compose/              # docker-compose.yml (all services)
  infra/monitoring/           # Prometheus, Grafana, Alertmanager configs
  config/                     # JSON risk/policy configs
  data/bot1/                  # Bot state, fills, minute logs, conf
  docs/                       # Strategy specs, ops runbooks
  BACKLOG.md                  # All known gaps with AI-executable specs — CHECK THIS FIRST
  infra/env/.env.template     # All required env vars
```

## Non-negotiables before touching production
- All changes must compile: `python -m py_compile hbot/controllers/runtime/kernel/controller.py`
- Architecture contracts must pass: `PYTHONPATH=hbot python -m pytest hbot/tests/architecture/ -q`
- Promotion gates must pass: `cd hbot && python scripts/release/run_strict_promotion_cycle.py`
- Never commit `.env` (only `infra/env/.env.template`)
- Bot1 is paper-only. `BOT_MODE=paper` in compose. Do not change connector to `bitget` without completing go-live checklist.

## Key files
- Runtime kernel: `hbot/controllers/runtime/kernel/controller.py` + mixins (`quoting_mixin.py`, `supervisory_mixin.py`, `telemetry_mixin.py`, `state_mixin.py`, `startup_mixin.py`, `regime_mixin.py`, `calibration_mixin.py`)
- Strategy adapter: `hbot/controllers/epp_v2_4.py` (thin adapter over kernel)
- Simulation engine: `hbot/simulation/desk.py`, `matching_engine.py`, `portfolio.py`
- Paper bridge: `hbot/simulation/bridge/hb_bridge.py`
- Platform utils: `hbot/platform_lib/core/utils.py`, `platform_lib/market_data/`
- Bot1 config: `hbot/data/bot1/conf/controllers/epp_v2_4_bot_a.yml`
- Compose: `hbot/infra/compose/docker-compose.yml`
- Backlog: `hbot/BACKLOG.md`
- Architecture tests: `hbot/tests/architecture/` (import boundaries, coverage minimums, regression baseline)
- CI pipeline: `.github/workflows/architecture_contracts.yml`

## Robustness standards (enforced by architecture tests)
- Zero `print()` in production code (controllers/services/simulation/platform_lib, excluding CLI dirs)
- Zero import boundary violations (platform→no ctrl/svc/sim; simulation→no ctrl/svc; controllers→no svc; no cross-service)
- All `except Exception: pass` blocks have justification comments
- All `# type: ignore` comments have mypy error codes
- Minimum test counts enforced per module area (controllers≥50, services≥50, architecture≥5)

## Before starting any task
1. Read `hbot/BACKLOG.md` for the full task spec including pre-answered design decisions
2. Check if relevant tests exist in `hbot/tests/`
3. After changes: compile + run `python -m pytest hbot/tests/ -x -q --ignore=hbot/tests/integration` from workspace root with `PYTHONPATH=hbot`

## Model complexity guide
Some tasks benefit significantly from a more capable model. Flag this to the user when relevant.

| Use a capable model | A fast model is fine |
|---|---|
| Modifying runtime kernel mixins (risk, edge, regime, quoting) | Config YAML edits |
| Implementing any P0 backlog item | Checking bot status / reading logs |
| ROAD-10 / ROAD-11 (ML pipeline) | Minor doc updates |
| New service design or architecture decisions | Running analysis scripts |
| Walk-forward backtest engine (ROAD-2) | Simple one-line fixes |

When spawning subagents for exploration or file search, a fast model is appropriate.
For implementation and reasoning about strategy correctness, use the best available model.
